    {
        "SurahNumber": 46,
        "AyahNumber": 3,
        "Tafseer": "\"We did not create the heavens and the earth and what is between them except in truth and for a specified term. But those who disbelieve, from that of which they are warned, are turning away.\" (3)\n\nThis is an expression of regret over the state of those who are persistent on denying this noble scripture sent down by the Exalted in Might, Wise God, and are turning away from that of which they are warned.\n\nThe Purposeful Nature of This World Requires the Day of Recompense\n\n'from that of which they are warned' ('amma undhiroo) points, obviously, to the Resurrection, and the Resurrection is such a reality that without believing in it, this entire system of the universe is reduced to a completely purposeless and vain play; whereas Allah Almighty created this universe with truth (bil-haqq), i.e., with a purpose and end. Allah Almighty, alongside being Exalted in Might (meaning Dominant and Powerful), is also Wise ('Al-Hakeem'). If there were no Resurrection, looking at this world would prove that its Creator's power is infinite; but at the same time, it would have to be accepted that He has performed a completely purposeless and vain work. Whereas, this is contrary to His apparent attributes. Just as His power is obvious from this world, His wisdom is also observed, and both of these attributes are present side-by-side. Remember that when attributes are mentioned without a coordinating conjunction, as is in 'Al-Aziz al-Hakeem', it means these attributes exist in the qualified entity simultaneously.\n\n'except in truth and for a specified term' (illa bil-haqqi wa-ajalin musamma)—meaning just as this universe's being with truth is clear, its being with truth naturally requires that the world does not continue forever as it is, but must have a specified term, after which it ends and His court of justice is established, so that whoever earned goodness receives its reward, and whoever earned evil faces its punishment.\n\nA Question and Its Answer\n\nHere, a question might arise in someone's mind: 'It appears rational that every person receives reward or punishment for their good or bad deeds, but why is it necessary that this entire world ends after a specified term; is it not possible that it remains as it is, and those who die have their decisions made?' This question is produced due to various misconceptions, which cannot be discussed here; however, we point to one thing: a person's every deed, whether good or bad, possesses infectious characteristics. A person sows a seed of goodness, from whose blessings the progeny of Adam benefits for centuries; similarly, a person devises a wrong and misleading philosophy, whose deviation wraps a vast creation, and then with the passage of time becomes so established that let alone uprooting it, generations of nations spend their capabilities to protect it. Due to this situation, to give a person a correct estimate of his deed, it is necessary that its far-reaching consequences are brought before him, and those elements of the universe which witnessed his deed testify. Without this, perfect justice cannot stand manifest. For this reason, it is necessary that the term of this world is completed, and Allah Almighty judges in such a court where everyone is present, and even the heavens and the earth are called to testify with all their records if required. This is possible only when the Day of Recompense is one for everyone."
    },
    {
        "SurahNumber": 46,
        "AyahNumber": 4,
        "Tafseer": "\"Say, 'Have you considered that which you invoke besides Allah? Show me what they have created of the earth, or have they partnership in the heavens? Bring me a scripture before this or a trace of knowledge, if you should be truthful.'\" (4)\n\nThere is No Proof in Favor of Shirk\n\nThis strikes at the primary cause of their turning away—showing that since they rely on their assumed partners and intercessors, they do not care about the warnings of the Qur'an. Their assumption is: first, the Resurrection is an empty threat, and second, those deities whom they worship will save them from every danger. It states: ask these people: 'Have you ever reflected on those deities whom you call upon besides Allah—whether they have any reality, or are they merely the creations of your own mind! If you consider them to have some reality, show me what they have created of the earth, or what is their share in the creation of the heavens!' The meaning is: they can be partners of God only if they have some share in the creation of the heavens and the earth. If they have no share, what is the meaning in associating them in His rights Who is the Creator of the heavens, the earth, and all that is between them. He, being the Creator, how will He tolerate that others become owners of His created world! And how have you allowed associating others in His sovereignty and His rights without His permission! It should be kept in mind that the Arab polytheists accepted Allah Almighty as the Creator of everything; therefore, this proof is based on an accepted belief of theirs.\n\n'Bring me a scripture before this or a trace of knowledge, if you should be truthful'—'Atharah' refers to that tradition which is transmitted from the predecessors. 'Al-Atharatul-baqiyyatu minal-ilm' means: 'yathuroonahu minal-awwaleen' (they transmit it from the predecessors). The restriction 'of knowledge' (min 'ilmin) is to show: the foundation of this tradition must be on knowledge, not on mere assumption.\n\nThe Credible Medium to Know the Testimony of God\n\nThat is: if you claim that God has associated your deities in His divinity, then to prove your claim, present either some Book before this Qur'an, or some tradition whose foundation is on knowledge, not on assumption. The meaning is: whether He has any partner or not—in this, the primary testimony is His alone: has He associated anyone as His partner, and whom? The sole medium to know His testimony is His Books, or those traditions which have been correctly transmitted from His prophets and messengers. It states: present any such thing; do not ruin your Hereafter by building a castle in the air on the basis of mere assumption.\n\nIt should be clear that the knowledge sent down by Allah was transmitted to creation either through His Books—such as the Torah, the Gospel, etc.—or through traditions—such as the teachings of Hazrat Ibrahim (peace be upon him) which reached subsequent generations through traditions. Within these sources, there is no testimony in favor of shirk. Although many distortions have occurred in the Torah, the Gospel, and other scriptures, they contain no trace of shirk. Similarly, the traditions transmitted regarding Hazrat Ibrahim (peace be upon him) in the Torah, the Gospel, or other scriptures contain no trace of shirk. The Arab polytheists claimed to follow their ancestors, but despite the repeated challenges of the Qur'an, they were unable to prove that their ancestral way was based on any traditional or rational proof. Until the end, they said only: 'We will continue walking on that way on which we found our ancestors,' without any concern for where they received this way."
    },
    {
        "SurahNumber": 46,
        "AyahNumber": 5,
        "Tafseer": "\"And who is more astray than he who invokes besides Allah those who will not respond to him until the Day of Resurrection, and they, of their invocation, are unaware. And when the people are gathered [that Day], they [i.e., the deities] will be [rendered] enemies to them and will be deniers of their worship.\" (5-6)\n\nThe Insignificance and Heedlessness of the Polytheists' Deities\n\nThis is an expression of regret over the state of these simpletons—showing that who can be more astray and unfortunate than those who call upon other deities besides Allah who will not respond to their calls until the Day of Resurrection, and who are unaware that anyone is calling upon them! On the Day of Resurrection, let alone receiving help from them, they will be their enemies and will send curses upon them.\n\nMost of the things the polytheists worshipped had no actual existence; therefore, the question of their being aware of anything or accepting any call does not arise. And those entities which do exist—such as the angels and the Jinn whom the Arab polytheists worshipped, or Hazrat Isa (peace be upon him) whom the Christians worshipped—cannot be aware of anyone's calls themselves, let alone being able to accept them. In Surah Al-Ma'idah, it is: Allah will ask Hazrat Isa (peace be upon him) on the Day of Judgment whether he commanded the people to take him and his mother as deities besides Allah, and he will reply: 'How could I say that to which I have no right! I told them only what You commanded me. After me, what they fabricated is not in my knowledge. You alone know it.'\n\nIn Surah Al-Furqan, the angels' reply is quoted in these words:\n\n'And the Day He will gather them and that which they worship besides Allah and will say, \"Did you mislead these, My servants, or did they [themselves] stray from the path?\" They will say, \"Exalted are You! It was not for us to take any allies besides You. But You provided comforts for them and their fathers until they forgot the message and became a ruined people.\"' (17-18).\n\nThis shows: as far as the prophets and the righteous are concerned, they will place all the responsibility on those who, contrary to their teachings, made them partners of God and worshipped them. As for other deities—such as the Jinn, devils, etc.—how they will declare their disassociation from their worshippers, and how their worshippers will curse them, has been described in various places, clarifying the reality: on the Day of Judgment, let alone being beneficial to them, they will be their worst enemies. Have a look at what we wrote under verses 62-64 of Surah Al-Qasas."
