    {
        "SurahNumber": 46,
        "AyahNumber": 7,
        "Tafseer": "\"And when Our clear verses are recited to them, those who disbelieve say of the truth when it has come to them, 'This is obvious magic.'\" (7)\n\nExcuses to Turn away from the Qur'an\n\nThis describes those excuses which they devised to turn away from the Qur'an. It states: when Our highly clear verses of Tawhid and the Resurrection are recited to them and they have no answer to them, they say regarding the Qur'an: 'This is obvious magic.' We have explained the reason for calling the Qur'an magic in various places: when the leaders of the Quraysh had to accept its influence and sway, they tried to convince their common people: 'this discourse is indeed highly powerful, but this is no proof of its being the word of God; this is merely the magic of words.'\n\nIn 'of the truth when it has come to them' (lil-haqqi lamma ja'ahum), 'when it has come to them' points to the gravity of their action: they declared this truth to be magic when it came to them. No misunderstanding regarding the truth is surprising as long as it has not come before us. But after its coming, only those make such excuses who want to remain in delusion and try to keep others in delusion."
    },
    {
        "SurahNumber": 46,
        "AyahNumber": 8,
        "Tafseer": "\"Or do they say, 'He has invented it'? Say, 'If I have invented it, then you do not possess [power to protect] me from Allah at all. He is most knowing of that [slander] in which you engage. Sufficient is He as a witness between me and you, and He is the Forgiving, the Merciful.'\" (8)\n\nAnother Propaganda of the Opponents\n\nThis is a reference to another propaganda of the opponents. Since this was a highly absurd propaganda, whose absurdity was clear even to those who committed it, its mention has occurred in a highly interrogative style, leaving the answer to Allah—showing: 'If you, in the madness of opposing me, have gone to the extent of declaring me a fabricator contrary to your own conscience, then any further debate with you is useless. Allah Almighty Himself will decide this matter.'\n\n'Say, \"If I have invented it, then you do not possess [power to protect] me from Allah at all\"'—meaning: tell them: 'If I have fabricated such a great lie against God, nothing will save me from His grasp, and at that time, you will be of no use to carry the burden of this crime of mine.'\n\n'He is most knowing of that [slander] in which you engage'—'afadha fil-hadeeth' has been explained. Its actual meaning is to criticize some matter to the extent of making a mountain out of a molehill. The meaning is: Allah is fully aware of the slanders you are fabricating; therefore, I refer the matter to Him. He alone will decide whether I am a fabricator, because of which you do not give me any weight, or if, knowing me to be upright and trustworthy, you declare me a fabricator purely because my invitation is contrary to your desires.\n\nThe Obstinate's Misconception is Left to Allah\n\n'Sufficient is He as a witness between me and you'—in this dispute, Allah is sufficient as a witness between me and you. It should be clear: when it is known that the opponent has resorted to stubbornness and defiance, and is saying what is contrary to his own conscience, in such conditions, the only way remaining for a decent person is to refer the matter to Allah and end the debate. This decent method sometimes directs even the obstinate to evaluate their attitude. Even if they are not influenced, from the perspective of invitation, this is the most blessed method. People of impartial minds are influenced by it, and the respect of the inviter increases in the hearts of the opponents due to his self-confidence.\n\n'and He is the Forgiving, the Merciful'—meaning: 'I refer this matter to Allah, and I hope He will judge, and it will become clear to everyone whether I am a fabricator or you are denying the truth. Even if there is some delay in this decision, there is no cause of despair for me. I know my Lord is Forgiving and Merciful. He does not hasten in seizing, but grants respite until the final limit so that those who wish to repent and reform may do so.'"
    },
    {
        "SurahNumber": 46,
        "AyahNumber": 9,
        "Tafseer": "\"Say, 'I am not something new among the messengers, nor do I know what will be done with me or with you. I only follow that which is revealed to you, and I am not but a clear warner.'\" (9)\n\nThat is: if you are opposing me because I am a human like you and cannot show the punishment of which I warn, remember that I am not the first messenger in the world. Many messengers have passed before me. They were all human. None of them was superhuman. The Sunnah of Allah regarding the messengers is that they have always come from among the humans; and hear also: if I cannot bring the punishment according to your demand, this too does not negate my claim to messengership. I have claimed to be a messenger, not God or the knower of the unseen. I openly admit: I do not know what Allah Almighty will do with me, nor what He will do with you. I only follow what is revealed to me, and inform you of it. In accordance with the guidance of Allah, I am only a clear warner to you. Beyond this, neither do I carry any responsibility, nor do I claim to be anything more. The meaning is: if you have to discuss with me, discuss regarding my actual claim, instead of raising unrelated questions to entangle yourselves and others."
    },
    {
        "SurahNumber": 46,
        "AyahNumber": 10,
        "Tafseer": "\"Say, 'Have you considered: if it was from Allah, and you disbelieved in it while a witness from the Children of Israel has testified to something similar, and he believed while you were arrogant? Indeed, Allah does not guide the wrongdoing people.'\" (10)\n\nHere, the apodosis (jawab al-shart) is omitted, and this omission points to the reality: the apodosis contains such terrifying consequences that words are incapable of expressing them. The meaning is: you are denying this Book with great audacity and declaring it my fabrication against God, but what if it was indeed from Allah! At the same time, this is also worth reflecting: a witness from the Children of Israel has testified to something similar, and believed, while you are turning away out of arrogance!\n\nWho is Meant by the Witness?\n\nHere, the question arises: who is pointed to by the witness? Our commentators have given three answers to this question.\n\nThe general view is that this refers to Hazrat Abdullah bin Salam, but another group has criticized this, stating: Abdullah bin Salam believed in Islam long after the sending down of this Surah in Medina; so what is the sense in referring to his testimony in this Meccan Surah before his accepting of Islam, when there is no minor context to declare even this verse as Medinan.\n\nThe second group has interpreted this as Hazrat Musa (peace be upon him), but this view is also not weighty. Below, the mention of Hazrat Musa (peace be upon him) and the Torah is coming independently by name to refer to their testimony for the Qur'an; so what is the need to refer to them here in the form of an allusion?\n\nA third group has taken it in the generic sense to mean those general people of the Children of Israel who believed in the Qur'an. Ibn Kathir is also in this group, but this view is entirely baseless. Taking it in the generic sense is contrary to the rules of the language. But we do not want to go into details here. The style of the discourse is witness: the indefiniteness is to magnify its status, not to express insignificance and generality; therefore, it is necessary that this points to some witness whose status and testimony are such that they can be presented as proof.\n\nIn our view, this points to Lord Masih (peace be upon him). Some of its reasons are as follows:\n\n1. First, Hazrat Isa (peace be upon him) stated the purpose of his advent: 'I have come to clear the path of the one to come.' After him, the Prophet (pbuh) was mبعوث, and you are the final Prophet and final Messenger; because of this, there is no minor room to interpret this as anyone other than the Prophet (pbuh). If you study the Gospels, it stands manifest: just as before Hazrat Isa's (peace be upon him) advent, Allah Almighty sent Hazrat Yahya to give glad tidings of Hazrat Isa, similarly, before the Prophet's (pbuh) advent, He sent Hazrat Isa (peace be upon him) to clear His path. In the Gospels, the primary theme that is expressed in various styles is the glad tidings of the Prophet (pbuh). The mentor-scholar has written a treatise in English on this subject—showing: the primary objective of the Gospels is the praise and introduction of the Prophet (pbuh). The heavenly kingdom of which Hazrat Isa (peace be upon him) repeatedly spoke, and the parables he described, are entirely applicable to the Prophet (pbuh) and the invitation of the Qur'an.\n\n2. Second, although the glad tidings of the Prophet (pbuh) is also present in the Torah, the Psalms, etc., whose references we have quoted, Hazrat Isa (peace be upon him) gave His glad tidings with the specification of his name. In Surah As-Saff, it is:\n\n'And [remember] when Jesus, the son of Mary, said, \"O Children of Israel, indeed I am the messenger of Allah to you confirming what came before me of the Torah and bringing good tidings of a messenger to come after me, whose name is Ahmad.\" But when he came to them with clear proofs, they said, \"This is obvious magic.\"' (As-Saff: 6).\n\nThe glad tidings referred to by the Qur'an in this verse is present in the Gospels. In some Gospels, the very name of the Prophet (pbuh) has occurred repeatedly—for instance, in the Gospel of Barnabas (which the Christians declare fabricated for this reason, but it makes no difference, because in other Gospels, his reference is present). Although his name has been removed to leave only his attributes, anyone who reflects honestly will accept: no one besides the Prophet (pbuh) can be its مصداق. We limit our discussion to an allusion here. God willing, further details will follow in the commentary of Surah As-Saff.\n\n3. Third, Hazrat Isa (peace be upon him) clearly described the Qur'an, its invitation, its character, its dominance, and the stages of this dominance in his prophecies. We have referred to some in Surah Al-A'raf, and will also discuss under verse 29 of Surah Al-Fath. For the satisfaction of readers, some are quoted here as well:\n\n'Jesus said to them, \"Have you never read in the Scriptures: 'The stone the builders rejected has become the cornerstone; the Lord has done this, and it is marvelous in our eyes'? Therefore I tell you that the kingdom of God will be taken away from you and given to a people who will produce its fruit. Anyone who falls on this stone will be broken to pieces; anyone on whom it falls will be crushed.\"' (Matthew 21:42-44).\n\n'And I will ask the Father, and he will give you another advocate to help you and be with you forever.' (John 14:16).\n\n'I will not say much more to you, for the prince of this world is coming. He has no hold over me,' (John 14:30).\n\nThere are also references in various parables to the gradual success of the Islamic invitation. One parable, to which the Qur'an has referred in Surah Al-Fath, is this:\n\n'He told them another parable: \"The kingdom of heaven is like a mustard seed, which a man took and planted in his field. Though it is the smallest of all seeds, yet when it grows, it is the largest of garden plants and becomes a tree, so that the birds come and perch in its branches.\"' (Matthew 13:31-32).\n\n4. Fourth, this clear testimony of Hazrat Isa (peace be upon him) had the effect: those among the Christians who remained firm on the actual Christianity, i.e., the followers of Simon, believed in the Qur'an with great enthusiasm after its sending down, and the Qur'an praised them in beautiful words. In Surah Al-Ma'idah, this group is mentioned as:\n\n'You will surely find the most intense of the people in animosity toward the believers [to be] the Jews and those who associate partners with Allah; and you will find the nearest of them in affection to the believers those who say, \"We are Christians.\" That is because among them are priests and monks and because they are not arrogant. And when they hear what has been revealed to the Messenger, you see their eyes overflowing with tears because of what they have recognized of the truth. They say, \"Our Lord, we have believed, so register us among the witnesses.\"' (Al-Ma'idah: 82-83).\n\nRead the commentary of these verses. Since people are not familiar with the history of the Christians, the correct meaning has not been clear to them. This is not the praise of Paul's followers, but of Simon's followers. Paul's followers do not call themselves 'Nasara' (Christians), but 'Masihi' (Christians). Simon's followers indeed called themselves 'Nasara'. They held that testimony which Hazrat Isa (peace be upon him) gave of the advent of the final messenger, and when the time arrived, they testified with true faith. Pointing to this, they said: 'Our Lord, we have believed, so register us among the witnesses.' They did not fall into that arrogance in which Paul and his followers fell; because of this, they achieved the favor of Islam. Regarding these people, Hazrat Isa (peace be upon him) prophesied: 'Blessed are the poor in spirit, for theirs is the kingdom of heaven.' Above, in the verse of Surah Al-Ma'idah, their attribute is mentioned as: 'and because they are not arrogant.'\n\nThis clarified that the nature of Hazrat Isa's (peace be upon him) testimony is entirely different from a general testimony. His advent was specifically to clear His path and inform the creation of that heavenly kingdom which was to appear through you. With this reference, the Qur'an established proof against both the polytheists and the People of the Book. We mentioned that in this period, the Quraysh received the support of the People of the Book, because of which their confidence increased. The Qur'an showed here: the Jewish, Christian, and Quraysh opponents may commit whatever actions they wish today, but a glorious witness of the Children of Israel has testified to this truth and believed in it. After his faith and testimony, those who oppose this truth purely out of arrogance should reflect on their end.\n\n'Indeed, Allah does not guide the wrongdoing people'—this refers to that Sunnah of Allah which He has appointed regarding guidance and deviation—showing that He never guides those who wrong their own souls and disregard His light. He made His truth completely clear through the guidance of reason, the testimony of the horizons, and the testimony of His prophets. Now, those who try to make all these things a means of their deviation, Allah is not responsible to guide them. He leaves them to wander."
    },
    {
        "SurahNumber": 46,
        "AyahNumber": 11,
        "Tafseer": "\"And those who disbelieve say of those who believe, 'If it had been good, they would not have preceded us to it.' And when they are not guided by it, they will say, 'This is an ancient falsehood.'\" (11)\n\nThe Arrogance of the Deniers\n\nThis explains that arrogance of the deniers which was mentioned in the preceding verse—showing that their arrogance is such: they present as proof against the truth that it was accepted first by the poor; thus, their wealthy say: 'If there was any good in this new religion, it was impossible that these poor people preceded us to it.' Their meaning is: no other blessing of this world has been received by them; therefore, if this had been a real blessing, they would not have preceded us, but we would have preceded them. Their preceding us is proof that there is no good in it, but it belongs to those things which are sought by low-class people.\n\n'And when they are not guided by it, they will say, \"This is an ancient falsehood\"'—meaning now, after being blinded by this light, they will not limit their statement to this, but will also say: 'This lie is nothing new; it has been coming from ancient times; in every era, there have been some who warned of such things to establish their hold, but their word has never turned true. The Resurrection of which they warned has neither come nor will it ever come. The lie of such people has been exposed; therefore, we are not going to fall for their threats.'\n\n'Those who disbelieve' (alladhina kafaroo), as the context indicates, refers to the wealthy of the disbelievers, whose arrogance was mentioned in the preceding verse. 'of those who believe' (lilladhina amanoo) refers to the poor Muslims, and 'li' (for/of) is in the sense of 'fi' (in/regarding), as has passed.\n\n'And when they are not guided by it' shows that when they denied a highly clear truth, to satisfy their own conscience and to deceive people, they had to fabricate other statements; thus, they would also say: 'This lie is highly ancient.' In declaring it an ancient lie, the proof, in their assumption, is that its being a lie has been proven. If the Resurrection is to come, where has it been; there has been its mention from a long period, but it has not appeared."
    },
    {
        "SurahNumber": 46,
        "AyahNumber": 12,
        "Tafseer": "\"And before it was the Scripture of Moses to lead and as a mercy. And this is a confirming Book in an Arabic tongue to warn those who have wronged and as good tidings to the doers of good.\" (12)\n\nReferring to the Torah's Testimony for the Qur'an\n\nThis refers to the Torah's testimony for the Qur'an. Although in terms of chronological order, its mention was to precede, for those specific reasons to which we pointed, Hazrat Isa's testimony was mentioned first. Now, referring to the Torah, the continuity of this testimony is shown—showing: before it, the Book of Moses came to lead (imam) and as a mercy. 'Imam' means a leader and guide. This is exactly what has been described with 'guidance and mercy' (huda wa rahmah) for the Qur'an, and we have explained: these two words are used keeping both this world and the Hereafter in view—the Book of Allah guides in this world, and becomes a means of His mercy in the Hereafter. Its actual status is of an 'Imam' (leader). Just as the following of the Imam is necessary, following this Book in the affairs of life is obligatory. If its status does not remain, then regardless of how much verbal respect is shown, it is of no use with Allah.\n\nThe Qur'an is the Fulfillment of the Torah's Prophecies\n\n'And this is a confirming Book in an Arabic tongue'—this points to the Qur'an, showing that it has been sent down in the Arabic language as the fulfillment of the Torah's prophecies. Just as Hazrat Isa (peace be upon him) testified, Hazrat Musa (peace be upon him) also prophesied. These prophecies were waiting for their fulfillment. With the sending down of the Qur'an, this fulfillment appeared, and in this way, the Qur'an confirmed the Torah.\n\nGenerally, people have assumed: since the Qur'an accepts the Torah as a divine Book, the Qur'an also must be a divine Book. This is entirely baseless. The Qur'an's accepting of the Torah as a divine Book is indeed a proof of the Torah's being divine, but how does it prove the Qur'an's being divine? The Torah's testimony for the Qur'an's being divine is possible only if it contains prophecies regarding the Qur'an and its presenter, and the sending down of the Qur'an and the advent of the Prophet (pbuh) confirm these prophecies in such a way that no fair-minded person can deny it, but every honest person proclaims: 'Indeed, the true fulfillment of these prophecies has appeared, and has confirmed them.' Allah Almighty has described the Qur'an as the confirming Book of those scriptures in this very sense, and not in the sense people have generally assumed. The Qur'an accepts those scriptures as divine, but also declares them محرف; therefore, this confirmation is not absolute, but in this specific sense. For this sense, the word 'tasdeeq' (confirmation) is well-known in Arabic. Its explanation has passed.\n\n'in an Arabic tongue to warn those who have wronged'—this is an expression of favor upon the Arabs, and also points to some of the Torah's prophecies. The aspect of favor is clear: Allah Almighty sent down this Book in Arabic to elevate their language, grant it eternal survival, choose them to deliver His religion and testify to it, and end their every excuse.\n\nPointing to previous prophecies: in the Torah, it is present that the final messenger's advent will be among the unlettered, i.e., the Children of Ismail. The language of these unlettered was, obviously, Arabic; because of this, referring to their language is pointing to them.\n\nThe Objective of the Qur'an\n\n'and as good tidings to the doers of good'—this is the second objective of this Book, and since this is the primary objective, it is in the form of a noun. It states: this is a great and eternal glad tidings for the doers of good (Al-Muhsineen). 'Muhsineen' is used here in contrast to 'those who have wronged', which sheds light on the meaning of the word: it refers to those who protected all their capabilities and kept their lives within the limits of their Creator."
    },
    {
        "SurahNumber": 46,
        "AyahNumber": 13,
        "Tafseer": "\"Indeed, those who have said, 'Our Lord is Allah,' and then remained steadfast - there will be no fear concern them, nor will they grieve. Those are the companions of Paradise, abiding eternally therein as recompense for what they used to do.\" (13-14)\n\nPointing to a Specific Aspect of the Good Doers' Character\n\nThis explains that glad tidings mentioned in the preceding verse, and points to a specific aspect of the good doers' character—showing: those of Our servants who accepted the invitation of the Qur'an and declared: 'Our Lord is Allah' and then, being safe from every fear, remained steadfast on this declaration, for them is the glad tidings of eternal Paradise; neither will they have any fear regarding the future, nor any grief regarding the past; they will be the owners of Paradise eternally, and they will receive this as a reward for their deeds."
