        "SurahNumber": 46,
        "AyahNumber": 15,
        "Tafseer": "2. Subsequent Theme: Verses 15–20\n\nNext, to console the Prophet (pbuh), it is clarified: what kind of people will accept this Book, and what kind will remain averse to it. The description of those who wrong themselves and the doers of good above is explained in detail here. This clarifies: those who are of upright nature, who possess intellect, who control their emotions, and who recognize their parents' rights, will also perform their duties to their Lord. The invitation of the Qur'an will appeal to them. As for those who lead a life free of any restrictions and duties, no good is to be expected of them. They will walk on their own path and face that end which is destined for such negligent ones. Recite the verses.\n\n3. Analysis of Words and Explanation of Verses\n\n\"And We have enjoined upon man, to his parents, good treatment. His mother carried him with hardship and gave birth to him with hardship, and his gestation and weaning period is thirty months. [He grows] until, when he has reached maturity and has reached forty years, he says, 'My Lord, enable me to be grateful for Your favor which You have bestowed upon me and upon my parents and to work righteousness of which You approve and make righteous for me my offspring. Indeed, I have repented to You, and indeed, I am of the Muslims.'\" (15)\n\nThe Development of the Consciousness of Rights within an Upright Nature\n\nThis, as we pointed out, explains how the development of the consciousness of rights occurs in an upright human nature. It states: We have instructed man to show good treatment to his parents. This instruction is imbued within human nature, and was also taught by His prophets and good servants. This has been accepted in all religions from the beginning: after God, the greatest right upon man is of his parents; rather, it is also not wrong to say: as far as the consciousness of rights is concerned, the right of parents is the first to be realized. Then, from this, man progresses to the consciousness of His rights. As long as a child is young, he considers his parents to be everything, because whatever he receives, he receives from them; but when he reaches maturity, he realizes: the true Sustainer is He Who brought his parents into existence as well. Thus, holding the parents' finger, he reaches God, and a greater right is realized within him, and these two are the greatest rights, from which other rights branch off.\n\nThe right of parents upon their children is: when children become powerful and parents old, they do not consider them a burden, but remember: once they were placed in their lap as a lump of flesh, but they, instead of considering them a burden, considered them the light of their eyes and estimated them to maturity. The right of their favor is: keep the wings of obedience and love always lowered for them. Do not consider serving them a burden, nor utter any word of aversion to them.\n\nThe Mother's Selfless Sacrifices for Her Child\n\n'His mother carried him with hardship and gave birth to him with hardship, and his gestation and weaning period is thirty months' points to those sacrifices which every mother must bear for her child. This is meant to draw attention to the reality: no child can fully fulfill the right of his parents' favor. It states: for months, his mother carried him in her womb with hardship, and then, playing the game of life, gave birth to him. After this, the period of weaning came, and for two years, she made her blood milk to feed and nurture him. The meaning is: who else can bear such pains for him with joy? then, what a great ungratefulness it would be if he forgets this favor, and when they stand in need of his favor, shows indifference to them!\n\nHere, it is noteworthy that good treatment is demanded for both parents, but the three sacrifices mentioned belong specifically to the mother, and no sacrifice of the father is mentioned. Its reasons, in our view, are as follows:\n\n1. First, in reality, the share of the mother in the initial nurturing is far greater than the father's share. In a Hadith, the Prophet (pbuh) made the mother's right three times greater than the father's. This Hadith is based on this verse.\n\n2. Second, the mother belongs to the weak sex. This also requires that the child serves and obeys her more than his father.\n\n3. Third, the child's material interests are associated with the father. They are to inherit his property; for this reason, there is less fear of negligence or disobedience regarding him, whereas regarding the mother, such expectation is less; therefore, those who do not possess the correct consciousness of her sacrifices do not value her.\n\nA Subtle Derivation\n\nFrom 'and his gestation and weaning period is thirty months' (wa-hamluhu wa-fisaluhu thalathoona shahran), some commentators among the companions derived the conclusion: the minimum period of gestation is six months. This is because here, the period of gestation and weaning is stated to be thirty months, and in another place, the Qur'an clarifies that the period of weaning is two years. If we subtract two years from thirty months, six months remain for gestation, which shows that the minimum period of gestation is six months. This derivation is subtle, and traditions suggest that Hazrat Uthman Ghani and Hazrat Ali agree with it.\n\nThe Consciousness of Parents' Rights Is the Guide to His Rights\n\n'until, when he has reached maturity and has reached forty years...'—meaning: the upright nature of the one who recognizes his parents' rights, when he reaches maturity, necessarily stirs up the consciousness of His rights. Within the compassion of his parents, he sees a reflection of His mercy and lordship, and from here, finds the path to reach his true Sustainer Who arranged for his parents' care. As if: the consciousness of one right raises him to perform another greater right. If the consciousness of parents' rights is not awakened within anyone, he cannot reach His rights. To reach this destination, the guide is parents' rights, and whoever has not opened this door, the path ahead remains blocked.\n\nIt states: such an upright person, on reaching maturity, particularly forty years, supplicates before his Lord: 'O my Lord, hold me so that I show gratitude for Your favors which You have bestowed upon me and upon my parents, and perform those righteous deeds which are pleasing to You, and grant me righteous successors in my offspring, I turn to You in repentance, and I covenant to be of Your obedient servants.'\n\nThe primary time for this consciousness to awaken is youth, which is expressed with 'reached maturity' (balagha ashuddahu), but in the birth of maturity, the primary factor is not age alone, but environment, training, etc. also have a major share; because of this, a single age of maturity cannot be specified for everyone. Thus, our scholars differed, and for this, there are reasons. In our view, Allah Almighty, keeping in view the weaknesses of our nature, has kept vastness in this, and forty years ('arba'eena sanah') is mentioned as its final limit. The meaning is: after reaching youth, this consciousness should be awakened within every upright human; and if some barriers prevented it, on reaching forty years, it must necessarily be awakened. If it is not awakened even at this age, it is a sign that this person has distorted his nature.\n\nThis indicates: the Merciful, Generous Lord, keeping in view our weaknesses, has kept some consideration up to forty years. The reason is: until this age, passions and desires are dominant. A person, in trying to reform himself, is often overcome by desires to lose the path. After forty years, the force of desires is broken. If a person does not try to follow them wrongly, he can control them; because of this, after this, he must not expect any further allowance.\n\nIt should be kept in mind: what has been stated here is said keeping in view the general human nature and general human environment, and not keeping in view an entirely Islamic environment. In a corrupt society, barriers are more; because of this, Allah Almighty shows special consideration to those who try to reform themselves in such a society. In an Islamic society, these barriers are absent; because of this, responsibility in it is greater.\n\nSupplication for Maturity\n\n'Awzi'nee' (Enable me) has been explained. It means: hold me, restrain me, i.e., until now I have been swept away by emotions, but now grant me the capability to show gratitude for Your favors which You have bestowed upon me and upon my parents instead of being swept away. This feeling of gratitude is the foundation of the entire religion.\n\n'and to work righteousness of which You approve'—the feeling of gratitude necessarily becomes the motivator for righteous deeds, and righteous deeds are those performed for the pleasure of Allah Almighty instead of following desires. In this path, sometimes a person faces the misconception that he commits an action, in his own assumption, for the pleasure of God, but it becomes a cause of His anger. For example, those deeds which apparently are of virtue, but contain some mixture of shirk or innovation. For this reason, a person must continuously supplicate that Allah Almighty grants him the capability to perform those virtues which are in accordance with His pleasure.\n\n'and make righteous for me my offspring'—meaning alongside, he also supplicates for his offspring: that righteous successors are raised among them, so that they are a cause of honor in the world, and their virtue becomes intercession in the Hereafter. This has passed in 'And grant us from among our wives and offspring comfort to our eyes...'.\n\n'Indeed, I have repented to You, and indeed, I am of the Muslims'—this is his covenant for the future: 'Now I have turned to You, and I covenant to be of Your obedient servants.'"
    },
    {
        "SurahNumber": 46,
        "AyahNumber": 16,
        "Tafseer": "\"Those are the ones from whom We will accept the best of what they did and overlook their misdeeds, [to be] among the companions of Paradise. [That is] the promise of truth which they had been promised.\" (16)\n\nIt states: these are the ones from whom We will accept their good deeds and overlook their lapses.\n\n'among the companions of Paradise' (fee as-habil-jannah) is in the state (hal). That is: they will be dealt with in the manner that those deserving of Paradise are dealt with. They will be counted in their ranks.\n\n'the promise of truth' (wa'd-as-sidq) is a verbal noun—meaning for them is this true and firm promise of Allah Almighty, in whose violation there is no fear.\n\nWarning to Those Who Reach Forty Years of Age\n\nThis verse is, as we pointed out, an encouragement and also a warning to the young, and particularly to those who have reached forty years of age—showing: now the final hour to wake up has arrived. If they do not open their eyes even now, they will deprive themselves of Allah's consideration."
    },
    {
        "SurahNumber": 46,
        "AyahNumber": 17,
        "Tafseer": "\"But one who says to his parents, 'Uff to you; do you promise me that I will be brought forth [alive] when generations before me have already passed [into oblivion]?' while they call to Allah for help, [saying], 'Woe to you! Believe! Indeed, the promise of Allah is truth.' but he says, 'This is not but legends of the former peoples' -\" (17)\n\nThe Mention of Those Who Lead a Life Free of Any Restrictions\n\nThis is the mention of the other group.\n\nIn Parables, 'Al-Ladhee' (the one who) Need Not Be Specific\n\nWe have been clarifying: when 'Al-Ladhee' comes for a parable, it is not necessary that it refers to some specific person, but it refers to anyone upon whom the parable is applicable. In verse 92 of Surah An-Nahl, a highly clear example has passed. Here too, it is general. Thus, in the subsequent verse, its mention has occurred in the plural. Those who are unfamiliar with this style of Arabic try to find some specific person for 'Al-Ladhee' everywhere, and wander far from the correct meaning; thus here also, some have interpreted this as Hazrat Abdur-Rahman, the son of Hazrat Abu Bakr. Although commentators have refuted this, since their refutation is not based on a firm principle, the question remains: if 'Al-Ladhee' is for a specific, who is meant? Having understood our explanation, this question does not arise.\n\nA Negligent Attitude\n\nThis is the mention of the group in contrast to the group above. It states: those young ones who lead a life free of any restrictions do not get the opportunity to evaluate their attitude. Their parents reproach their bad conduct and remind them of God and the Hereafter, but they rebuke them: 'Do you warn me that I will be raised alive from the grave after dying and decaying? This is a completely meaningless statement. Countless creations have passed before me, none of whom has returned alive, so how can I believe that I will be raised alive after death! These are the legends of the former peoples. In every era, some people have said such things to overawe others, but their word has never turned true. The Resurrection of which they warned has neither come nor will it ever come. The lie of such people has been exposed; therefore, we are not going to fall for their threats.'\n\nAlthough 'Wayl' (Woe) is among the words of curse, in some places, it also comes to express compassion, affection, and duls-o-and. In Arabic classical texts, excellent examples are present. Here too, it is in this very context. Parents, with great compassion, say to him: 'Woe to you! Do not be stubborn, abandon your bad conduct, believe, and fear the Hereafter.' But instead of valuing their compassion, he rebukes them."
    },
    {
        "SurahNumber": 46,
        "AyahNumber": 18,
        "Tafseer": "\"Those are the ones upon whom the word [of punishment] has come into effect, among communities which had passed before them of jinn and men. Indeed, they [all] were losers.\" (18)\n\nThe Fate of the Negligent\n\nThis describes their end. Here, allusions, pronouns, and verbs are in the plural. To the extent that 'Al-Ladhee' has become 'Alladhina' (those who). This is clear proof that the preceding verse did not mention a specific person, but a specific category of people. It states: these are the ones upon whom Allah's word came into effect. Allah's word refers to that statement He made in reply to Iblis's challenge—stating: 'Whoever follows you from among the jinn and men, I will fill Hell with you all.' 'among communities' (fee umamin) is in the same context as 'among the companions of Paradise' in the preceding verse—meaning they will join those Jinn and men who, before them, led a negligent life like them to ruin their Hereafter."
    },
    {
        "SurahNumber": 46,
        "AyahNumber": 19,
        "Tafseer": "\"And for all there are degrees [of reward or punishment] for what they did, and that He may fully compensate them for their deeds, and they will not be wronged.\" (19)\n\nThe Fate of Both Groups\n\n'All' (Kull) refers here to both groups mentioned above. It states: both groups will receive ranks and degrees in accordance with their deeds. Those who recognized and performed the rights of their parents and their Lord will achieve the high ranks of Paradise, and those who led a negligent life will enter that depth of Hell which they deserve. 'Degrees' (Darajat) is used here by way of dominance (taghleeb).\n\nAfter 'and that He may fully compensate' (wa-liyuwaffiyahum), a conjoined clause is omitted according to the well-known rules. We have opened it in the translation."
    },
    {
        "SurahNumber": 46,
        "AyahNumber": 20,
        "Tafseer": "\"And the Day those who disbelieved are exposed to the Fire [it will be said], 'You exhausted your good things during your worldly life and enjoyed them, so this Day you will be recompensed with the punishment of [extreme] humiliation because you were arrogant upon the earth without right and because you were defiantly disobedient.'\" (20)\n\nAlthough in 'And for all there are degrees...' above, the results of the deeds of both groups were mentioned briefly, since the addressees specifically are the arrogant of the Quraysh, their end is described with special care. It states: remember that Day when these arrogant ones will be presented before Hell and told: 'The blessings destined for you, you exhausted them in the world. Now, for you is only the punishment of disgrace, because you showed arrogance in the earth without right and disobeyed His commands.'\n\n'You exhausted your good things' (Adhhabtum tayyibatikum) means you finished your share of blessings. Those whom Allah Almighty blesses with His favors in this world, if they remain grateful and perform the rights of His servants, they also accumulate a treasure of blessings for their Hereafter. On the contrary, those who fall into arrogance upon receiving blessings finish their entire treasure here, and in the Hereafter, only their consequence will be their share.\n\nDescribing arrogance with 'without right' (bighayril-haqq) is to show: all blessings are bestowed by Allah Almighty, so what right does anyone have to boast upon receiving them? A person should boast only if he is the creator of something and achieved it without God's bestowing. When everything is the gift of God, boasting is sheer ignorance, and a greater ignorance is that a person uses His blessings in His disobedience."
    },
    {
        "SurahNumber": 46,
        "AyahNumber": 21,
        "Tafseer": "4. Subsequent Theme: Verses 21–28\n\nNext, the story of Hazrat Hud (peace be upon him) and 'Aad is described briefly. The objective is: first, to present historical proof for that retribution of Allah which was mentioned in verses 41-42 above—showing that after the nation's denial, the decision regarding them is necessarily made, whether during the messenger's life, or after his migration or death. This retribution is His appointed Sunnah, from whose grasp no nation has escaped. Even a giant like Pharaoh, when he fell under its grasp, was drowned along with his armies. His power was of no use to him.\n\nSecond, this is an example of that reality which was mentioned in verse 40—stating that those who destroy their capability to understand and choose deviation deliberately cannot be guided by any sign. They remain blind even after seeing the greatest miracles. Their eyes open only when they see His punishment.\n\nThird, this is a testimony to that reality which was mentioned in verse 45—showing that all messengers sent by Allah brought the very same invitation of Tawhid which the Qur'an is presenting. No messenger ever invited to the worship of anyone besides Allah Almighty... Recite the verses.\n\nAnalysis of Words and Explanation of Verses\n\n'And remember the brother of 'Aad, when he warned his people in the [region of] al-Ahqaf - and warners had already passed before him and after him - [saying], \"Worship not except Allah. Indeed, I fear for you the punishment of a tremendous Day.\"' (21)\n\n'The brother of 'Aad' refers to Hazrat Hud (peace be upon him), who was sent as a messenger to 'Aad. Since he was a member of 'Aad, he was called their brother. The messenger's being from within his nation holds various benefits for the establishment of proof, which we have been clarifying.\n\n'Al-Ahqaf' lexically refers to long tracts of sand, but here it refers to that desert which is situated between Oman, Yemen, Najd, and Hadramaut, and which was the home of 'Aad. By referring to this name, the Qur'an has drawn attention to the great destruction which came from this region. Obviously, during the peak of 'Aad's power, this region must have been highly fertile and filled with those cultural monuments for which 'Aad was famous. But now, it is a barren desert where no one can imagine that any trace of culture would have existed. I believe that this region was named Al-Ahqaf after their decline, when only sand tracts remained in place of magnificent buildings.\n\n'and warners had already passed before him and after him'—this is a parenthetical clause in the middle. The meaning is: Hazrat Hud's (peace be upon him) warning was nothing new; warners had passed in the adjacent regions before, and the traces of the punishment they warned of were present, but just as their predecessors did not learn, these successors did not benefit from their warner's warning.\n\nThe Root of All Corruption Is Shirk\n\n'\"Worship not except Allah. Indeed, I fear for you the punishment of a tremendous Day\"'—this is Hazrat Hud's (peace be upon him) primary warning: he warned his nation not to worship others besides Allah. 'If you do not desist, I fear that a painful Day's punishment will come upon you.' This shows that the root of all corruption is shirk, from which other corruptions branch out; therefore, Allah's messengers warned of this first, and stated its end: if they do not reform, they will fall under His punishment. Shirk is rebellion against Him in His earth; therefore, when proof is fully established against a nation through His messenger, and they do not desist, they receive no further respite."
    },
    {
        "SurahNumber": 46,
        "AyahNumber": 22,
        "Tafseer": "\"They said, 'Have you come to us to turn us away from our gods? Then bring us what you promise us, if you should be of the truthful.'\" (22)\n\nThe Nation's Demand for the Punishment, and His Reply\n\n'Ifk' means lie, and the preposition 'an' (from/away) is an indication that it encompasses some verb which means turning away. That is: they replied to Hazrat Hud: 'Have you come as a messenger to turn us away from our deities through your lies of messengership and punishment! If so, bring that punishment of which you are warning; without this, we are not going to believe you.'"
    },
    {
        "SurahNumber": 46,
        "AyahNumber": 23,
        "Tafseer": "\"He said, 'The knowledge is only with Allah, and I convey to you that with which I was sent; but I see you [to be] a people behaving ignorantly.'\" (23)\n\nHazrat Hud (peace be upon him) replied to their demand: 'To warn you of this punishment was commanded to me by Allah Almighty. Consequently, I have warned of it; as for when and in what form it will come, its correct knowledge is with Allah Almighty alone. I cannot say anything regarding it, but I see that you are caught in extreme ignorance—that instead of planning to save yourselves from the great danger of which you are being warned, you are demanding to bring it. I am not the one who brings the danger, but the one who warns of it.'"
