    {
        "SurahNumber": 46,
        "AyahNumber": 24,
        "Tafseer": "\"And when they saw it as a cloud approaching their valleys, they said, 'This is a cloud bringing us rain.' Rather, it is that for which you were impatient: a wind, within it a painful punishment,\" (24)\n\nThe Manifestation of the Punishment, and Their Fate\n\nThe referent of the object pronoun is that punishment which was mentioned in the preceding verse. 'Aarid' means a cloud, and is in the state (hal). The meaning is: that punishment which they demanded, when they saw it as a cloud approaching their valleys, they rejoiced and said: 'This is a rain cloud which will water our valleys!' 'Rather, it is that for which you were impatient'—meaning they believed it to be a rain cloud, but the situation showed that it was that punishment which they demanded. 'a wind, within it a painful punishment' describes the nature of the punishment—showing that it was a furious wind within which was hidden a painful punishment. This wind is described as 'sarsar' in another place, which remained dominant over them for several days and destroyed them completely. In Surah Al-Haqqah, its mention is:\n\n'And as for 'Aad, they were destroyed by a screaming, violent wind Which He imposed upon them for seven nights and eight days in succession, so you would see the people therein fallen as if they were hollow trunks of palm trees.' (6-7)."
