    {
        "SurahNumber": 46,
        "AyahNumber": 29,
        "Tafseer": "6. Subsequent Theme: Verses 29–35\n\nNext, the Prophet (pbuh) is consoled in some verses—showing: if the people of your nation do not value this Book, do not grieve; this is no fault of yours or of this Book, but of their own nature; whereas the beauty and influence of this Book are such that when some Jinn heard its voice, they turned to it, and arose as its inviters to their nation. It is a matter of pity if those for whom this Book has been sent down do not recognize its worth.\n\nAfter this are the concluding verses of the Surah, which contain threats of punishment to the disbelievers and instruction of patience to the Prophet (pbuh). Recite the verses.\n\n7. Analysis of Words and Explanation of Verses\n\n\"And [remember, O Muhammad], when We directed to you a party of the jinn, listening to the Qur'an. And when they attended it, they said, 'Listen quietly.' And when it was concluded, they went back to their people as warners.\" (29)\n\nThe Nature of the Event of the Jinn's Hearing the Qur'an\n\nBy 'We directed to you' (sarafna ilayka), it is learned that the event of the Jinn's hearing the Qur'an occurred by the planning of Allah. Neither did the Prophet (pbuh) make any arrangements for it, nor did the Jinn intend it beforehand. Rather, Allah directed their party on the way to listen to the Prophet (pbuh) reciting the Qur'an. Consequently, they listened, and its effect upon them was: they became its devoted ones, and arose as its inviters to their nation.\n\nTraditions suggest that this event occurred when you returned in sadness from Ta'if; in Nakhlah, you spent the night. There, in one of the night prayers, you were reciting the Qur'an. On that occasion, this party of Jinn heard, and experienced that effect which is mentioned here. By mentioning this, the objective is: those for whom and in whose language this Book has been sent down, and for whose reform the messenger of Allah is dedicating His day and night, traveling to Ta'if, are not ready to hear it, but treat the messenger badly; and the Jinn are such that when they hear some verses on the way, they stand in awe, and arise as its inviters to their nation. This shows: the fault lies not in the Qur'an or its presenter, but within those who turn away.\n\nSatire on the Wicked of Makkah and Ta'if\n\n'And when they attended it, they said, \"Listen quietly\"'—meaning as soon as they heard the voice of the Qur'an, they instructed their companions to listen to this divine discourse modically and quietly, so that His mercy descends upon them. Referring to their respect is a satire on the bad conduct of the wicked of Makkah and Ta'if, who instructed their gang: 'do not listen to this Qur'an, but create disruption so that its voice is suppressed.' In Surah Al-Jinn, their conduct is mentioned as:\n\n'And that when the Servant of Allah stood up supplicating Him, they almost became upon him a compacted mass.' (19).\n\nTestimony to the Sincerity of the Jinn's Impression\n\n'And when it was concluded, they went back to their people as warners'—this is a testimony to the sincerity of their impression, showing that they did not limit themselves to saying: 'excellent, glory be to God, what Allah willed!'; but arose to warn their nation of that danger of which this Book warned. It should be kept in mind: those who say 'excellent' are found in the worst of times, but this is of no value until some practical change occurs in life. Those who praise the eloquence of the Qur'an are numerous today, but those who act upon it are rare. The state of these Jinn is described: the Book affected them to the extent that they arose as its inviters to their nation, regardless of all dangers."
    },
    {
        "SurahNumber": 46,
        "AyahNumber": 30,
        "Tafseer": "\"They said, 'O our people, indeed we have heard a Book revealed after Moses confirming what was before it which guides to the truth and to a straight path. O our people, respond to the Caller of Allah and believe in Him; He will forgive for you of your sins and protect you from a painful punishment. And he who does not respond to the Caller of Allah will not escape on earth, and he will not have besides Him any protectors. Those are in clear error.'\" (30-32)\n\nThe Invitation of the Jinn to Their Nation\n\nThis is the invitation they presented to their nation. First, they introduced this Book: it has been sent down after Hazrat Musa (peace be upon him) as the fulfillment of those prophecies which were present in previous scriptures. It should be clear: after Hazrat Musa (peace be upon him), the Prophet (pbuh) is the only presenter of the Shariah; all other prophets before him followed Hazrat Musa's (peace be upon him) Shariah. Similarly, before the Qur'an, the primary Book was the Torah, and its being divine is proven by the fact that the Qur'an came as the precise fulfillment of those prophecies present in the Torah and other scriptures.\n\n'which guides to the truth and to a straight path'—this same point has passed through the tongue of these Jinn in Surah Al-Jinn with a minor change of words: 'We have indeed heard a wonderful Qur'an, which guides to the right way, so we believed in it and we will never associate anyone with our Lord.' (1-2). Comparing these two verses shows: 'truth' (Al-Haqq) refers to the belief of Tawhid which is the straight path to reach God; the word 'Haqq' points to the robust nature of this belief and its being in accordance with reason and nature, and 'straight path' (Sirat-e-Mustaqeem) points to its being easy and free of deviance. The indefiniteness is to magnify its status.\n\n'O our people, respond to the Caller of Allah and believe in Him...'—this is the primary invitation they presented to their nation: 'respond to the Caller of Allah and believe in Him.' 'and believe in Him' explains 'respond'—showing that faith is the primary thing. Those who believe, Allah will forgive them of their sins and protect them from a painful punishment.\n\nThe Severity of the Matters of Human Rights\n\nIn 'of your sins' (min dhunoobikum), 'min' (of) is for part—showing that some sins are such whose forgiveness remains pending even after faith. In my view, these are the major sins relating to human rights (Huquq-ul-Ibad). For their forgiveness, it is necessary that a person compensates for them. If compensation is not made, or the opportunity has passed, His justice requires that this matter is presented in the Hereafter. What decision will be made is known only to Allah, but it is clear: not compensating when the opportunity is there is contrary to the requirement of faith, and if the opportunity has passed, it is hoped that a person's sincerity, repentance, remorse, and those virtues he performs until his death will intercede for him.\n\nUnjust Hope Is a Fitnah like Despair\n\nThose who have interpreted 'min' as redundant have not fulfilled its right. There is no redundant letter in the Qur'an, and it should be kept in mind: just as unjust despair is not permissible regarding Allah, unjust hope is also a fitnah. Moderation is between fear and hope.\n\n'And he who does not respond to the Caller of Allah will not escape on earth, and he will not have besides Him any protectors. Those are in clear error'—although this can be from Allah Almighty, parallels indicate that it is a part of the Jinn's statement. In Surah Al-Jinn, their statement is:\n\n'And that we have become certain that we can never escape Allah on earth, nor can we escape Him by flight.' (12).\n\n'and he will not have besides Him any protectors' relates to the Hereafter—meaning: just as in this world they cannot escape from Him, in the Hereafter, no protector will save them from Him.\n\nA Question and Its Answer\n\nHere, a question arises: are the Jinn addressed by the Qur'an exactly as humans are, and is the Prophet (pbuh) their messenger as He is ours? If the answer is in the negative, what is the meaning of their statement: 'O our people, respond to the Caller of Allah and believe in Him'?; and if in the affirmative, has the Sunnah of Allah regarding the messengers been changed? The Sunnah is: they were sent from within the nation they invited, spoke their language, lived among them, and established proof against them. After this, if the nation denied, he declared disassociation, migrated, and the nation was destroyed. Can it be claimed that the Prophet (pbuh) performed all these duties among the Jinn as He did among humans? Obviously not; then, can the life of a human be a perfect model for the Jinn, when we know that the life of an angel or a Jinn cannot be a model for us? Thus, the Qur'an stated in reply to those who demanded why a human was sent instead of an angel: how could an angel be sent for the guidance of humans? If an angel was sent, he would have to come in human form.\n\nMoreover, when Jinn and humans were created from two opposite elements, their natures, temperaments, social and cultural needs, and commands must be different. They can share only the basic principles of Tawhid, the Hereafter, and good and evil; other matters must be different; therefore, the Qur'an can guide them only in terms of beliefs and moral principles. In other matters, they need messengers from among themselves to guide them in accordance with their natural demands, needs, and conditions, so that proof is established against them.\n\nThis is what the Qur'an also shows. The Jinn's impression of the Qur'an was not known directly to the Prophet (pbuh), but was revealed to him. This very impression is quoted with greater detail in Surah Al-Jinn, where it is explicitly stated that you were informed of this through revelation: 'Say, [O Muhammad], \"It has been revealed to me that a group of the jinn listened and said, 'Indeed, we have heard a wonderful Qur'an...'\"' (1). If you had been their messenger, you would have known of this directly. You would have performed the duty of invitation among them as you did among the Arabs, but the Qur'an does not show this. Some traditions suggest that some groups of Jinn came to you, and you went to them, but first, these traditions contain such contradictions that they stand in need of evaluation, and second, they show at most: sometimes they met you. This is not sufficient to prove that you performed the duty of messengership among them.\n\nAs for their praising the Qur'an and inviting their nation to believe, this is entirely correct. We pointed out: as far as the basic principles of religion are concerned, they are shared between humans and Jinn, rather among all creations—birds, mountains, sun, and moon. For this reason, just as the birds and mountains joined Hazrat Dawud (peace be upon him) in His praise, this party of Jinn heard the Qur'an and was moved to invite their nation to believe in Tawhid, the Hereafter, and the punishment of God. Look at their invitation here and in Surah Al-Jinn; you will find that they mentioned only those matters which are shared. This proves that the basic invitation of the Qur'an is identical for both, but it is not correct to say that the Prophet (pbuh) was their messenger as He was ours. Those who held this view held it contrary to the Sunnah of Allah which has been described in detail in the Qur'an.\n\nAnother within-discourse point should also be pointed to.\n\nIn the preceding verses, for the Jinn who believe, only protection from the painful punishment is mentioned, and they are not explicitly given the glad tidings of Paradise; because of this, it has been attributed to Imam Abu Hanifah (ra) that he did not believe in the entry of the righteous Jinn into Paradise, or at least he was cautious in stating this explicitly. We cannot understand this caution of the Imam. When Hell is destined for their wicked ones, why would their righteous ones remain deprived of Paradise? Some have presented this proof in support: no one has any right established upon God; therefore, if He does not admit someone to Paradise despite his righteousness, this is not contrary to His justice. In our view, this proof is entirely baseless. No other can establish any right upon God, but His justice and mercy require that He fulfills those promises He has made of His own accord to His righteous servants, whether they be of humans or Jinn. We believe: Imam Abu Hanifah (ra) must have said: 'the righteous Jinn will not enter that Paradise which is for humans.' If he said so, it has a context. God willing, we will discuss this in detail in the commentary of Surah Al-Jinn."
